title: For Sale/Trade:  AA ARMS INC. AP9 NEVER FIRED
postcontent:
The AP9 is a pistol that was manufactured by AA Arms and distributed by Kimel Industries, Inc of Indian Trail, North Carolina, USA. AAArms began distributing the AP9 in the early 1990s and did so until 2001. The AP9 looks like a small submachinegun, but has no automatic fire function. This firearm is basically a large pistol that looks very much like the Intratec TEC-9. 

The standard AP9 has a 5" barrel; the AP9 target began with a 12" barrel (AP-9/12), but this was later reduced to 11" (AP-9/11 Target); they both have a separate fore end and a fluted barrel. These firearms were banned by most states after the passage of the Federal Assault Weapons Ban and other pieces of legislation, even after more cosmetic changes designed to make them appear to be less threatening. After the Federal Assault Weapons Ban of 1994 a ten round magazine was introduced. Original magazine capacities included 5 round, 10 round, 20 round and 32 round capacities.

title: For Sale:  Project Appleseed Rifle Marksmanship & Heritage Clinic
location: Knob Creek Range, West Point, KY, Louisville, Kentucky
postcontent:
Sep 8-9, 2012
Knob Creek Range
690 Ritchey Lane, West Point, KY 40177 
http://www.knobcreekrange.com/ 
Check-in starts at 8:30 AM. Course of Instruction begins at 9:00 AM each day.

This event is open to everyone.  Project Appleseed is an activity of The Revolutionary War Veterans Association, a 501(c)(3) all volunteer, non-partisan, non-profit organization, dedicated to teaching every American our shared heritage and history as well as traditional rifle marksmanship skills.  You may shoot anything from a .22 rimfire (the Ruger 10/22 and Marlin 795 are popular) to a centerfire such as an AR, AK, SKS, M1A or M1.  You will shoot approximately 250 rounds per day as you try to qualify as a Rifleman (210 Points) on a modified version of the AQT (Army Qualification Test) course of fire.


There are only 20 slots open for this clinic, so pre-registration is highly encouraged to make sure a spot on the line is reserved for you.  Politics are not discussed at Appleseed shoots, except for the politics of 1775. 


Some of the things you will learn-
Safe Rifle Handling - 4 safety rules
The 6 Steps to Firing the Shot
Building Solid Shooting Positions; Standing, Sitting and Prone.
Steady Hold Factors
Use of the GI Web Sling
Natural Point of Aim
Sight adjustment using inches, minutes and clicks
The Story of Our Nation’s Birth
The Lessons of April 19, 1775
The Debt We Owe to Our Forefathers
The Duty We Owe to Our Posterity


Pre-registration Fees (per person):
Active Military, Reserve, and Guard (w/ ID), Peace Officers (w/ ID), Disabled (w/ ID), Re-enactors in period dress, Elected officials (w/proof) shoot for free!
Youth (Under 21): $2.50 for one day or $5 for both days.
Women: $5 for one day or $10 for both days.
All others: $45 for one day or $70 for both days.
Hillside Plinkers Range Fee: $5 per adult shooter


Learn More, Find Directions and Register at:
http://www.appleseedinfo.org/search-states.php?filter=KY&statename=Kentucky


Our state Facebook page:
http://www.facebook.com/KentuckyRifleman


Rifles and ammunition are not supplied unless by pre-arrangement with the State Coordinator.

title: For Sale:  Custom High Quality Paracord Gun Slings
postcontent:
Looking for a unique sling for your favorite rifle or shotgun?  Why not try paracord?  Paracord, also known as 550 cord, is parachute cord with a breaking strength of 550lbs.  It is made from nylon materials with 7 inner strands in an outer core.  Total breaking strength is 550lbs, making a sling one of the strongest you'll ever find!  

Why paracord?  Easy - it's lightweight, unique, and is an essential tool for any survival situation.  The woven sling can be unwound to provide 80+ feet of usable 550 cord.  Should you ever get lost in the woods, cordage is handy for creating shelter, snares, tying off wounds, dragging game, or anything you can imagine.  The inner strands can even be separated out for use as fishing line or to sew wounds.  

Our paracord slings are made from authentic 550 paracord from a US military contractor, not that cheap Chinese crap!  Each sling includes swivels and is custom made to your desired length and color combination.  Choose from a wide variety of camo, solid colors, or just about any combination that you can imagine!  

Not only are paracord slings strong, they're also extremely supple and quiet.  The weave is stiff but has "give" to be comfortable on the shoulder no matter what you're carrying.  

Each sling is made to your custom order.  Simply reply to this ad with what you would like and we'll get right on it!  Turnaround time is a max of 2 weeks, but most often will be on its way to you in just days.

title: For Sale:  Crimson Trace Laser Grips LG-105 S&W J-Frame
postcontent:
Retail is $200+, asking $100. 

Great grips, but my only complaint is that there is no on/off switch for the laser grips. The laser is activated by a small sensitive button on the crimp portion of the hand (2nd knuckle from tip of fingers), and there is no on/off selector switch, thus you ultimately fire using the laser every time (of course unless you switch grips constantly). 

However, minus the lack of on/off switch these grips are extremely helpful for dry-fire practice to determine how much you're moving your hand just prior to fire. 

Also, a huge selling point for me was that these grips are low profile on the cylinder side of the gun allowing for easy-in use of speed loaders.

Grips are simple to install and come with a back-up set of batteries and all original packaging.

Located in Chico, CA and would be willing to drive as far as Yuba City, Red Bluff, or equal distance.

title: For Sale:  K31 (Karabiner Model 1931)
postcontent:
I've seen many of these and mine is in great shape.  I have only put 5 rounds through it.  It's a great rifle, just don't have any use for it. A friend of mine put it the right way, "they built these things they same way they build watches now." (Talking about the Swiss).  When you pull the trigger on it, it amazes you that this thing is as old as it is, so smooth.  All number match and everything works.  It comes with 25 rounds.

From Wikipedia:
The Karabiner Model 1931 (K31) is a magazine-fed, straight-pull bolt-action rifle. It was the standard issue rifle of the Swiss armed forces from 1933 until 1958, though examples remained in service into the 1970s. It has a 6-round removable magazine, and is chambered for the 7.5x55mm Swiss (also known as Gewehrpatrone 1911, GP11, or unofficially 7.5x55mm Schmidt Rubin), a cartridge with ballistic qualities similar to the 7.62x51mm NATO/.308 Winchester cartridge. Each rifle included a 6 round detachable box magazine with matching engraved serial number. A stripper clip loads the magazine from the top of the receiver.

The new, compact, daylight-bright SPARC (Speed Point Aiming for Rapid Combat) is packed with performance features and lends itself to a wide variety of firearm platforms—including AR15s, shotguns, and pistols. The modular three-piece base offers four separate mounting heights for user- and weapon-specific customization: 18.5mm (.725 inches), 22mm (.875 inches), 36mm (1.425 inches), 40mm (1.575 inches). Digital rear-facing and side controls for power on/off, dot brightness and night vision mode. Aircraft-grade 6061-T6 aluminum body. Get on target fast with the SPARC.


The versatile multi-height mount system of the SPARC accommodates AR15s needing absolute or lower 1/3 co-witness heights and uses a standard Weaver or Picatinny base (not included). The SPARC is also threaded to accept accessory ARD and comes with a 2x doubler.
